# Tests

- Test behavior, not implementation. Refactoring with the same behavior should not break the test.
- One logical assertion per test. Multiple `expect`/`assert` calls are fine when asserting facets of the same fact.
- Names are sentences: `"returns null when user not found"`, `test_throws_on_empty_payload`.
- Mock what you don't own (network, filesystem, time). Never mock what you own.
- Prefer fakes (in-memory implementations) over mocks for non-trivial contracts.

## Snapshots

- Use sparingly. They rot — pass on accidental drift unless humans review.
- Snapshot only stable, human-readable output. Never blob JSON.

## What to test

- Critical paths (auth, payments, data integrity): happy path + at least one failure.
- Edge cases: null, empty, max, concurrent, boundary values.
- Not: generated code, third-party internals, trivial getters/setters.

## Test data

- Builders / factories over 30-line literal objects.
- Include only fields the test asserts on.
